LOL, I love how you put that whole long disclaimer at the bottom, that was cute, I do that too sometimes if I&#39;m giving advice online, it does serve to keep things in perspective for people...

Ok, there are some things I want to mention right off the bat after half reading and half skimming your post... you talk about phosphenes... and I would have to agree that this is the correct term to use when talking about imagining these colors... they come in your phosphene field of vision rather than your &quot;mind&#39;s eye&quot; per se... I look at the minds eye and the phosphene field of vision as two separate things, one is imagination, while the other is fairly much quite a real field of vision...with eyes closed or the room dark, though other times you will see stuff as complementary color mild hallucinations on the white wall when you open your eyes and the room has some light...  

After reading Frank&#39;s post I did some of the visualizations going to bed last night... I noticed that the most difficult colors to shift to were yellow and blue, however eventually they all came, less distinctly on a wide scale, but very distinctly in snippets of my field of vision.  I also remarked the fact that - and this is just something that happens on its own pretty much every night without fail - as soon as I close my eyes I immediately begin to get involuntary images of psychedelics shapes colors objects and animations, but they all come and go so quickly in a series, that some of the scenes depicted, though my gut reacts like &quot;I recognize this&quot;, I&#39;m not given the chance to look at it long enough to pin a word on them and it is annoying, it&#39;s like that gut mood that&#39;s left hanging about you for a little while when you wake up in the morning from a dream you only half remember... where you remember the mood, but not the actual plot...  What do you call this phenomenon, of involuntary non eye-rubbing phosphenes... it&#39;s very very vivid and entertaining but its annoying that I have pretty much no control of the images and scenes that I end up seeing...
Last night after practicing colors I also practiced shapes, the triangle is the easiest one to begin to see on command, it comes almost instantaneously, the cross is another one that is not too difficult at all, the heart shape is one that took me a while, but I was able to produce it several times, though it never stuck around for long, though one time it did stick around long enough for me to see it as a fuzzy dark teal shape upon the lit wall when I opened my eyes... then there was the flower shape, and I began to half see it but not clearly, I got tired of doing  it and stopped, I&#39;m going to probably try again tonight...

Are these the kinds of exercises we are talking about, and if so do you have any specific tips on how to improve on the particular things I&#39;m doing?  Btw thank you for that post...


